  %h3{:style => "text-align: center"} Rules for VoterMedia BC Muni 2011 Competition

  %p
    In addition to the contest description on this page above, and the website terms at
    = link_to("votermedia.org/terms", "/terms") + ","
    the following also apply:
  %p
    As this is an experimental contest, we (the contest administrators) may change these rules
    during the contest as we see fit.
  %p
    We plan to mail award cheques at the end of the contest, for the accumulated daily winnings
    of each contestant. If desired, each contestant may request one interim payment of their
    accumulated winnings at any time during the contest.
  %p
    If a contest has only one contestant, that contest's award pool will be $10 per day.
    Contests with more than one contestant will have an award pool of $20 per day.
  %p
    Each city's contest will start on October 1, 2011, or when its first contestant has entered,
    whichever is later. Each city's contest will end on November 30, 2011, or when $1,000 has
    been awarded, whichever is earlier. (After that, the contest ballot will remain open, but with no awards.)
  %p
    Most of the content in a contestant blog's posts feed should relate to
    matters of interest to that city's residents. We reserve the right to drop a blog from a contest if,
    in our judgment, this condition is not maintained.
  %p
    Election candidates may enter their campaign blogs in this competition.
    FYI this is for the following reasons:
    %ul
      %li openness and competition;
      %li it gathers election-relevant blogs onto one page;
      %li candidates are knowledgeable and may offer helpful insights about the election;
      %li it creates an interesting test of whether voters prefer to fund political campaigns or independent media;
      %li some non-candidate blogs may be very partisan anyway, or even shills for candidates;
      %li
        contest administrators should not be trying to figure out which blogs are truly "independent"
        (whatever that means); that distinction is for the voters to make, if they care.

%br